entry.title: Deduplicate some WPT.
entry.content:
storagemanager-estimate and estimate-indexeddb are more or less the

same tests, the latter having been ported from the former to use

`async`/`await`. The former probably should have been deleted when the

latter was introduced.



Since some of the tests are related to IndexedDB and some are not, this

change keeps the IndexedDB tests in the file called `estimate-indexeddb`

and keeps the basic tests in `storagemanager-estimate` (with minor

updates).



One wrinkle from the Chromium side is that the behavior of

`storageManager.estimate()` is not actually specced, and as the Chromium

implementation uses LevelDB, which behaves in mysterious ways, adding

things to the database does NOT always increase the reported usage size.

Both of these tests operate on large things, which typically do increase

usage, however we noticed that for one reason or another, the test that

adds an *uninitialized* ArrayBuffer starts failing on Windows if

durability is set to relaxed. There are other ways to make the test fail

as well: using a shorter name for the database, or putting small

values, does not reliably increase the reported usage. This is all fine

in the sense that it isn't defined behavior, but it does suggest that

working in this area or on tests of this ilk is a bit of a minefield.

These tests probably should not exist as WPT, at least not until quota

behavior is specced (see https://github.com/whatwg/storage/issues/110).

But it would also be sort of a shame to delete WPT that are passing, so

I've left them in place for now.

entry.title: [Extensions] Add extensions::ServiceWorkerKeepalive
entry.content:
Extension service workers can have associated keepalives for a

variety of reasons, such as API calls or events. These are currently

implemented through subsequent calls to ProcessManager's

IncrementServiceWorkerKeepaliveCount() and

DecrementServiceWorkerKeepaliveCount(). This means each call site

has to perform those calls, store an associated UUID, and possibly

check the validity of the BrowserContext before decrementing.



Introduce a helper class, ServiceWorkerKeepalive, that adds RAII-style

behavior for this functionality. The ServiceWorkerKeepalive increments

the keepalive count for the associated worker upon construction and

decrements it upon deletion (if and only if the browser context is

still valid).



Use this new struct in ExtensionFunction. Follow-up CLs will use it

in other sites that manually call the Increment/Decrement methods on

ProcessManager.

entry.title: [Extensions] Use script serialization in scripting API
entry.content:
Use the new scripts_internal::SerializedUserScript and script

serialization methods when registering content scripts in the

scripting API. The flow now entails:

- Converting an api::user_scripts::RegisteredContentScript object to a

api::scripts_internal::SerializedUserScript object, then

- Using our existing methods to convert the SerializedUserScript into

an extensions::UserScript.



Similarly, in the reverse, we go from UserScript -> SerializedUserScript

-> RegisteredContentScript.



This results in much simpler code and less reuse of parsing logic.



This CL should have no effective behavior change.

entry.title: Avoid UB signed integer overflow in histogram logic
entry.content:
SparseHistogramTest.AddCount_LargeCountsDontOverflow tests some overflow

cases in the histogram logic, seemingly with the intent of checking that

one of the APIs does not overflow when the other does.



But by using signed overflow, we hit undefined behavior when the other

API overflows, so the compiler is allowed to arbitrarily mangle our code

(though unlikely). Add wrapping functions to base/numerics and use

those instead.



Wrapping seems not ideal of behavior either, but given the test is

intentionally overflowing and didn't try to use, e.g., a saturating

operation, I'm assuming that wraparound is what this code wants.

entry.title: Remove full tree recalc rule set invalidation code
entry.content:
Rules that were considered universal, i.e., matching every element

for invalidation, would cause a kSubtreeStyleChange on the root element.

This was very much connected to the old type of RuleSet invalidation.



Removing the tracking of such selectors in

needs_full_recalc_for_rule_set_invalidation means we will invalidate

fewer elements in cases like:



#id * {}



where we now should only invalidate elements inside elements with

id="id". It does however mean we will traverse the whole tree for sheets with:



* {}

entry.title: Avoid memcpy(NULL) and memset(NULL) in base/pickle.cc
entry.content:
There is a specification bug in C, such that NULL, 0 may not be passed

to functions like memcpy or memset, despite it being a natural

representation of the empty slice. Although C++ broadly accepts NULL, 0

as the empty slice (a default constructed std::vector or std::span has

null data), it inherits this language bug from C.



Clang will not miscompile code based on this language bug, but it will

flag it in UBSan. And GCC will indeed miscompile based on this.

Hopefully [0] will be successful in trying to get this language bug

fixed. In the meantime, we should avoid tripping this.



The most straightforward way to avoid it is to condition memcpy and

memset on len != 0, but this is tedious. Instead, just use std::copy and

std::fill from . Those are defined to allow (null, 0).



[0] https://github.com/llvm/llvm-project/issues/49459#issuecomment-1753382089

In file included from ../../components/webcrypto/status.cc:5:

In file included from ../../components/webcrypto/status.h:13:

In file included from ../../third_party/blink/public/platform/web_crypto.h:36:

In file included from ../../third_party/blink/public/platform/web_crypto_algorithm.h:35:

In file included from ../../third_party/blink/public/platform/web_private_ptr.h:36:

In file included from ../../third_party/blink/renderer/platform/heap/cross_thread_persistent.h:8:

../../third_party/blink/renderer/platform/heap/persistent.h:8:10: fatal error:

'third_party/blink/renderer/platform/heap/heap_buildflags.h' file not found

extended to include more generated headers that blink_headers require.

that deps on blink_headers, so it'd be a cycle to also dep the other

way.



This fixes over 30 flaky build steps in the compilation of content_shell

alone. Other than webcrypto, those were:

obj/content/child/child/blink_platform_impl.o
